.TH LU\-KB 5 "2026-04-27" "logicutils 0.1.0" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
lu\-kb \- logicutils knowledge\-base language
.SH DESCRIPTION
The logicutils knowledge base is an indentation\-sensitive language
combining deductive, abductive, and constraint logic programming with a
small functional core. KB files are read by
.BR lu\-query (1)
and may be referenced from rule files consumed by
.BR lu\-rule (1).

A module is a sequence of top\-level
.IR items :
fact blocks, rule blocks, abductive blocks, constraint blocks, type
declarations, function definitions, relation declarations, instance
declarations, and import or export directives.

.SH SYNTAX
.SS Lexical structure
Lines beginning with
.B #
are comments. Indentation, expressed in spaces or tabs consistently
within a file, opens and closes blocks the same way Python does:
deeper lines belong to the immediately preceding header line.

.SS Facts
.RS
.nf
fact depends:
    main.o <\- main.c
    main.o <\- header.h
.fi
.RE
.PP
Each line in a fact block is a directed pair
.I "head <\- arg1 arg2 ..."
that is added to the predicate named on the
.B fact
line.

.SS Rules
.RS
.nf
rule stale(Target):
    depends(Target, Dep)
    newer(Dep, Target)
.fi
.RE
.PP
A rule head is followed by a body of goals. Goals are predicate calls,
.B not
goals, conditions, or
.B let
bindings. Variables begin with an uppercase letter; ground values are
identifiers, integers, floats, booleans, or strings.

.SS Abduction
.RS
.nf
abduce missing_source(File):
    depends(Target, File)
    not exists(File)
    explain "source file may need generation"
.fi
.RE

.SS Constraints
.RS
.nf
constraint valid_alignment(x: SampleId, y: Reference):
    x != y
    exists("{x}.fastq")
.fi
.RE

.SS Functions
.RS
.nf
fn align_cmd(sample, ref):
    "bwa mem {ref}.fa {sample}.fastq"
.fi
.RE
Pipelines use the
.B |>
operator and lambdas use
.IB args " => " expr \fR.\fP

.SS Types
.RS
.nf
type SampleId = String where matches("[A\-Z]{2}[0\-9]+")

data AlignResult:
    bam_path: Path
    quality:  Float where value >= 0.0
.fi
.RE

.SS Relations and instances
Relations are multi\-parameter type relations. Instances may be
declared outside the relation block, may host nested instances under a
.B where
clause, and inherit the constraints of every enclosing instance.

.RS
.nf
relation Processable(Input, Output, Engine):
    fn process(input: Input, engine: Engine) \-> Output

instance Processable(Dataset, Model, GPU):
    fn process(data, engine):
        train(data)

    instance Batchable(Dataset, Model) where Engine == GPU:
        fn batch_size(input): estimate_vram(input)
.fi
.RE

.SS Imports
.RS
.nf
import bio.alignment (align, index)
import utils.paths as P
.fi
.RE
.B import
may also appear inside any block, in which case its bindings are scoped
to that block.

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lu\-query (1),
.BR lu\-rule (1)
.SH AUTHOR
NEWSNIPER.
